er way ? ^ and how did language arise out of non-language ? ^ the standard evolutionary psychology approach to these questions posits an innately specified strongly constraining device for learning language . ^ the " why " question is answered by equating the set of possible languages with the set of learnable languages . ^ biological evolution through natural selection is often appealed to in order to answer the " how " question . ^ the learnable languages are claimed also to be the optimal languages in terms of the survival / reproductive success of language users . ^ in this talk i will argue that the evolutionary psychology view is flawed because it fails to take into account the complexity of the interacting dynamical systems that underlie human language . ^  har new framework for understanding language evolution is put forward that explicitly models these interactions : the  ame  ame model (  ame ) . ^ the  ame treats language as an emergent property of interacting " agents " whose behaviour is ^ the result of observational learning of other agents " behaviour . ^  ame , ^ the input to a learning agent is previously learned behaviour by another agent . ^ in computer simulations of iterated learning , linguistic structure emerges from randomness without natural selection . ^ i will demonstrate this and some ^ of the other features of the  ame that have been the subject of recent research . ^ for example : iterated learning gets round some long-standing learnability problems ; it shows why the " poverty of the stimulus " , far from ^ being a problem for learning , actually enables the evolution of syntax ; it can explain why some languages have some stable irregulars within otherwise ^ regular paradigms ; it predi cts certain  ame constraints on linguistic variation ; it provides a new way of looking at the difference between creolisation and language change ; and it removes many of the obstacles in the way of an explanation of the origins of language in homo sa